1. SPRING MESSAGING OVERVIEW
============================

1.1 Definition:
Spring Messaging is a Spring module that provides a unified programming model for message-based communication between applications or components using messages instead of direct method calls.

üìå It supports:
Asynchronous communication
Event-driven architecture
Loose coupling

1.2 Why Spring Messaging:
Decouples producer and consumer
Improves scalability
Enables async processing
Backbone for microservices communication

1.3 Message-Driven Architecture:
Definition:
Applications communicate by sending and receiving messages via channels instead of calling each other directly.

2. CORE SPRING MESSAGING CONCEPTS
==================================

2.1 Message:
Definition:
A Message is a wrapper that contains:
Payload (actual data)
Headers (metadata)

Example:
Message<String> message =
    MessageBuilder.withPayload("Hello").build();

Key Points:
Immutable
Type-safe
Header-based routing possible

2.2 MessageChannel:
Definition:
A MessageChannel is a pipe through which messages flow from producer to consumer.
Types:

DirectChannel
QueueChannel
PublishSubscribeChannel

2.3 MessageHandler:
Definition:
Consumes messages from a channel and processes them.

@Service
public class MessageConsumer {
    public void handle(String msg) {
        System.out.println(msg);
    }
}

3. SPRING INTEGRATION OVERVIEW
================================

3.1 Definition:
Spring Integration is an extension of Spring Messaging that implements Enterprise Integration Patterns (EIP).

üìå It enables:
System-to-system integration
Message routing
Transformation
Filtering

3.2 Spring Integration Architecture:
Components:
Message
Channel
Endpoint
Adapter
Gateway

4. CHANNEL TYPES (VERY IMPORTANT)
==================================

4.1 DirectChannel:
Definition:
Synchronous point-to-point channel.

Example:
@Bean
public MessageChannel directChannel() {
    return new DirectChannel();
}

Output:
Message processed immediately

Key Points:
Same thread execution
Fast
Blocking

4.2 QueueChannel:
Definition:
Asynchronous channel backed by a queue.

@Bean
public QueueChannel queueChannel() {
    return new QueueChannel();
}

Key Points:
Producer and consumer decoupled
Useful for buffering

4.3 PublishSubscribeChannel:
Definition:
Broadcasts messages to multiple subscribers.

@Bean
public PublishSubscribeChannel pubSubChannel() {
    return new PublishSubscribeChannel();
}

Output:
Message delivered to all subscribers

5. ENDPOINTS
=============

5.1 Service Activator:
Definition:

Connects a service method to a message channel.

Example:
@Service
public class OrderService {

    @ServiceActivator(inputChannel = "directChannel")
    public void process(String msg) {
        System.out.println("Processing: " + msg);
    }
}

Output:
Processing: Order Created

5.2 Transformer:
Definition:
Converts message payload from one format to another.

@Transformer(inputChannel="input", outputChannel="output")
public String transform(String msg) {
    return msg.toUpperCase();
}
Output:
HELLO

5.3 Filter:
Definition:
Allows or blocks messages based on condition.

@Filter(inputChannel="input")
public boolean filter(String msg) {
    return msg.startsWith("A");
}

5.4 Router:
Definition:
Routes messages to different channels based on logic.

@Router
public String route(String msg) {
    return msg.contains("PAY") ? "payChannel" : "orderChannel";
}

6. ADAPTERS
============

6.1 Definition:
Adapters connect external systems to Spring Integration.

Examples:
File adapter
JMS adapter
HTTP adapter

6.2 File Inbound Adapter:
@InboundChannelAdapter(channel="fileChannel")
public MessageSource<File> fileReader() {
    return new FileReadingMessageSource(new File("input"));
}

7. GATEWAYS
=============

7.1 Definition:
Gateway provides a method-based interface for messaging.
@MessagingGateway
public interface OrderGateway {
    void sendOrder(String order);
}

Key Points:
Looks like normal method call
Internally uses messaging

8. SPRING MESSAGING WITH SPRING BOOT
=====================================

8.1 Dependencies:
spring-boot-starter-integration
spring-messaging

8.2 Auto Configuration:
Auto-creates channels
Auto-configures messaging infrastructure
Minimal configuration needed

9. SPRING MESSAGING WITH MICROSERVICES
=======================================

9.1 Use Cases:
Event-driven microservices
Async communication
Loose coupling

9.2 Common Brokers:
Kafka
RabbitMQ
ActiveMQ

üìå Spring Messaging provides abstraction on top.

10. TRANSACTION & ERROR HANDLING
=================================

10.1 ErrorChannel:
Definition:

Handles messaging errors centrally.

@ServiceActivator(inputChannel="errorChannel")
public void handleError(Message<?> msg) {
    System.out.println("Error occurred");
}

11. SPRING MESSAGING vs REST
==============================
| Spring Messaging   | REST             |
| ------------------ | ---------------- |
| Asynchronous       | Synchronous      |
| Event-driven       | Request-response |
| Loose coupling     | Tight coupling   |
| Better scalability | Simpler          |

